# Sous-Marin ASUQTR : V.a How to Setup Development Environment for Missions (PC)

Created by Gabriel Tremblay, last modified on Jan 12, 2021

When you want to start development of new or existing states and missions on your PC

** [Prerequisites](#V.aHowtoSetupDevelopmentEnvironmentforMissions(PC)-Prerequisites)

## <u>Prerequisites</u>

* Your ASUQTR's Bitbucket account name and password
* A computer or VM running Ubuntu Desktop 18.04

You will see**Flexbe App** mentionned in the next section. For now, you only need to know that it is a software tool we use to design the sub's behaviors and missions.

![image2020-10-25_15-12-18.png](attachments/40697930/40697938.png)

## <u>Overview</u>

This is the setup you'll be using. On the same Ubuntu PC, you will be running**ROS,** your **ASUQTR packages** and the**Flexbe App**.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Pros :**

* You do not need to have a Jetson Xavier. This may be the case if your other dev team members are already using it for testing.
* This setup is portable since you may use it on your laptop.
* No possible errors in term of network communication with the Jetson Xavier.

**Cons:**

* Testing your states or missions may not be "pratically" possible. This may be the case if you worked on a state machine where you do a barrel roll : you will certainly use real life sensors to know when your roll is completed. Obviously, you don't have the sensor.
* It is impossible to test your code for object detection (vision system) because the software stack uses **jetson-inference**, which is only available on jetson platforms

## <u>Install ROS for ASUQTR</u>

This process is described here: [IV. How to install ROS and ASUQTR packages](IV.-How-to-install-ROS-and-ASUQTR-packages_34897922.html)

## <u>Start ROS and Flexbe</u>

After installing ROS and ASUQTR packages on your PC or VM, you can start the whole ASUQTR system with this command line:

```
roslaunch asuqtr_mission_management pc.launch
```

After launching, you will certainly see some errors from ROS. That is because the launch file you used is trying to launch nodes for hardware you dont necessarily have, like the Vectornav Vin100 IMU, or the PCA9685 used to communicate with motors. This will not stop your asuqtr\_mission\_executor node from running, which is the whole point of ROS.

After installing ROS and ASUQTR packages on hte **OPB**, you should now see 2 sub icons in the favorite bar. They allow to start flexbe:

![](attachments/36175900/37355598.png)

The **blue**sub is for the PC setup (without a jetson device). While ROS is running, click this blue sub to start the flexbe app.

Here is the Flexbe App GUI communicating with the **asuqtr\_mission\_executor** node started in the background :

![](attachments/36175900/37355599.png)

You can see "online" on the top left corner, which means the Flexbe app is correctly communicationg with the behavior engine and mirror, as indicated by the green text in the terminal window.

## <u>Start and use the ASUQTR Dashboard</u>

You can see the dashboard by accessing your VM's IP address on you physical machine's web browser **OR** by accessing **localhost** in your VM's web browser.

Next, you can simply plug in a USB controller (Xbox one, Ps4, Xbox360, Logitech, etc) and move the joysticks to interract with the sub. The joysticks will send command to the motors. You can press the **BACK/SELECT button to activate/deactivate the LQR control system.**

If Ubuntu is running on a VM, you might be prompted by Windows10 to know if you would like to plug your controller in the host (windows) or the VM(ubuntu). Just choose the one you prefer and access the ASUQTR Dashboard accordingly. If you don't, the web browser won't be able to see your controller commands

![](attachments/36175900/40697948.gif)

## <u>Conclusion</u>

**Congratulations** **!** You've successfully installed your state and mission development environment for PC! The next step in your learning journey shall be to follow a tutorial on how to develop states or missions on the Flexbe App.
